Location: The base of the Winterhold plateau. The Sea of Ghosts stretches north. Black water, white ice, screaming wind. The Singing Glacier is visible across the strait ΓÇö a blue-white spire that hums with a low, aching frequency. Hjolmar's Forge is inside it.

THE PHYSICS RULE
Read this to the table once. Repeat it when they forget.
The ice is frictionless. The tonal frequency from the Singing Glacier vibrates the sea ice at a molecular level. Nothing grips. Boots slide. Weapons skid. If you push something, it moves until it hits something else. If you push off something, YOU move until you hit something else.
Action equals reaction. Every force creates an opposite force. Jump off the back of the floe, the floe moves forward. Swing a weapon, the recoil slides you. Cast a spell with physical force, you skid backward. Fire an arrow, you drift.
You cannot steer mid-slide. Once moving, you move in a straight line until impact. The only people who break this rule: Saijah (air dash ignores terrain) and Davinia (can build ice structures to catch/redirect people).
The water is lethal. The Sea of Ghosts is black, near-freezing, and deep. Anyone who goes in takes 6 Cold damage immediately (irreducible) and must make a Hard (-2) Might check each round to stay afloat. Two failures and they sink. Rescue requires someone reaching the edge AND having a way to pull them out ΓÇö on frictionless ice, reaching down to grab someone means you slide in after them.

THE FLOE
The party's raft. A slab of sea ice roughly 40 feet across. It was part of the frozen shore until they broke it free. It is their vehicle for the entire crossing.
Floe Integrity: 10 segments.
Every collision costs segments. Track this privately.
Glancing hit: -1 segment
Direct collision: -2 segments
Catastrophic impact: -3 segments
At 7 segments: Cracks visible. The floe groans.
At 5 segments: Noticeably smaller. Characters are crowded. Anyone who slides now has less room before they reach the edge. Read aloud: "The floe has lost nearly half its mass. You can see the water through the cracks. There is barely room for all five of you."
At 3 segments: Critical. Someone is standing on a piece that's about to break off. Any collision at this point risks splitting the floe in two with party members on both halves.
At 0 segments: The floe disintegrates. Everyone is in the water. This is a TPK scenario unless they can get onto debris within 2 rounds.

PHASE 1: DEAD STOP
Read aloud:
"You step out of the base of the plateau onto the frozen shore. The wind hits you like a door slamming. Ahead, the Sea of Ghosts ΓÇö not frozen solid, but a chaos of ice and black water. Channels of open sea wind between massive floes. And across the strait, maybe half a mile out, the Singing Glacier. You can hear it from here. A low hum that you feel in your chest more than your ears.
At the shore's edge, a massive slab of sea ice sits half-grounded on the rocks. Forty feet across, flat, thick. It's connected to the shore by a thin bridge of frost. Beyond it ΓÇö open water, then the maze of ice.
The moment you step onto the slab, you understand the problem. Your boots find nothing. No grip. No traction. You slide. Everything slides."
What happens: Let them experiment. Someone will try to walk and slide across the slab helplessly. Someone will fall. Someone will grab someone and they'll both slide. Let it be funny for two minutes. Let them discover the physics with their bodies.
The actual problem: How do you get this thing moving? The floe is grounded. They need to break it free from the shore and generate enough force to push it into open water.
Let them solve it. Do not suggest solutions. Possible approaches they might discover:
Kyboh braces against the shore rocks and pushes the floe with raw Might. He stays on shore and has to jump onto the moving floe before it drifts out of reach.
Alfonso uses force magic against the shoreline to push the whole slab.
Everyone stands at the shore-side edge and jumps backward off the edge simultaneously. Combined mass = combined force. But then they're all sliding across a frictionless deck toward the far edge.
Orion's horn. A sustained note directed at the shore could generate enough resonance to vibrate the floe free. He'd need to brace against something.
Davinia freezes the contact point between floe and shore, expands the ice, and cracks them apart. She reads the stress fractures to find the weakest point.
The moment the floe starts moving: It doesn't stop. Phase 2 begins immediately. They don't get to celebrate.
≡ƒæü∩╕Å DAVINIA SEES (Phase 1): The ice beneath her feet isn't natural. Through the wizard eyes, the frictionless surface is a vibrating plane of tonal energy ΓÇö the same kind of frequency she saw in Kyboh's bones. The glacier across the water is broadcasting it. She can see the resonance field saturating every ice surface.
She can also see the floe's structure ΓÇö hairline fractures, density variations, weak points, strong points. She knows where it will break first if they hit something.
CROWN REACTION: Interest. Ismara recognizes tonal ice architecture. This is old. Older than the College. The whisper: "Someone built this. Long ago. The sea remembers."

PHASE 2: THE GAUNTLET
The floe is moving. It accelerates because there's no friction to slow it. Each obstacle appears with warning ΓÇö Davinia sees it first with her wizard eyes, then everyone sees it. The table has SECONDS to respond. Three characters can act. Two are bracing, holding on, or helpless.
Pacing rule: Describe the obstacle. Give the table 30-60 real-world seconds to decide who does what. If they argue too long, the obstacle hits. This is not cruel ΓÇö this is the frictionless ice demanding decisiveness. If they complain, remind them: "The ice doesn't wait."
Between obstacles, give them 1-2 minutes of calm. Let them talk, plan, catch their breath. Then the next one appears. The calm is part of the pacing. Tension comes from the contrast.

OBSTACLE 1: THE CHANNEL
Warning: "Dead ahead ΓÇö the ice ends. A channel of open black water, thirty feet wide. The floe on the other side is lower. You're heading straight for the gap. You have seconds."
The problem: The floe will sail off the edge of the ice shelf into open water and sink nose-first. They need to either bridge the gap, jump the gap, redirect, or find a way to keep the floe floating across.
Three-action solutions might include:
Davinia freezes the water in the channel to create a bridge (FP cost ΓÇö high)
Alfonso uses force magic to tilt the floe's leading edge upward so it ramps over the gap
Kyboh throws something massive off the front to slow their approach speed
Anyone who braces at the front acts as a counterweight
If they fail: The front edge dips into the channel. Black water floods across the front third of the deck. Anyone standing forward makes Agility TN 12 or they're ankle-deep and sliding toward the water. -1 segment. The floe survives but it's wet, cold, and people are hurt.
If they fail badly (nobody acts): The floe tips. Everyone slides toward the submerged front edge. Agility TN 14 or you're in the water. -2 segments. The floe rights itself but it's now barely moving and significantly smaller.

OBSTACLE 2: THE PILLAR
Warning: "A column of rock ΓÇö volcanic basalt jutting from the sea floor, coated in ice. It's directly in your path and it's not moving. Davinia, you see it through the mist five seconds before anyone else."
The problem: Direct impact will crack the floe. They need to shatter the pillar, steer around it, or brake.
This obstacle rewards Orion. His horn is the perfect tool. A sustained resonant frequency aimed at an ice-coated basalt column could shatter the ice shell and potentially crack the rock itself. He wouldn't know this unless he tries.
Three-action solutions might include:
Orion aims the horn at the pillar and blasts a sustained note. Tonal engineering roll. If he hits the resonant frequency of the ice coating, the pillar explodes into fragments before they reach it.
Kyboh moves to the side of the floe and shoves off the pillar as they pass ΓÇö redirecting both himself and the floe. Risk: he slides off the floe and has to be caught.
Davinia builds an ice wedge on the front of the floe to deflect off the pillar rather than hit it square. Turns a direct collision into a glancing blow.
Alfonso melts the base of the pillar with fire magic. Won't destroy it but might topple it before they arrive.
If they fail: Direct collision. Everyone makes Might TN 12 or gets knocked off their feet ΓÇö and on frictionless ice, off your feet means sliding. The floe cracks audibly and changes direction. -2 segments. The floe is now spinning slowly, which makes the NEXT obstacle harder.
If Orion shatters the pillar: This is his moment. Describe it cinematically. The ice shell cracks in spirals. The basalt beneath splits. The fragments rain across the water around them as they glide through the debris field. The horn's note echoes off the glacier ahead. He just learned that tonal engineering works on the physical environment, not just on enchantments.
≡ƒæü∩╕Å DAVINIA SEES (Obstacle 2): If Orion uses the horn, she sees the sound. Not metaphorically. The tonal wave is visible to her as a ripple in the resonance field saturating the ice. She can see it hit the pillar, find the harmonic frequency, and tear the structure apart from the inside. She has never seen tonal magic used this way before. It's not her domain ΓÇö but she can SEE it.
If she tells Orion what she sees ΓÇö "I can see the frequency, aim lower, the resonance is strongest at the base" ΓÇö give him Advantage on the roll.

OBSTACLE 3: THE CALVING
Warning: No warning. A massive section of glacier wall ahead shears off and crashes into the sea. A wave ΓÇö not huge, but on frictionless ice, any wave is a disaster.
The problem: The wave hits the underside of the floe and tilts it violently. Everyone slides toward one edge. The floe rocks like a boat in a storm. This isn't about steering ΓÇö it's about not falling off.
This obstacle rewards Saijah. Her air dash ignores terrain. While everyone else is sliding helplessly across a tilting frictionless surface, she can move freely. She is the rescue unit.
Three-action solutions might include:
Saijah air-dashes to whoever is closest to the edge and grabs them. She's the only one who can reach them in time.
Davinia builds a wall on the low edge to catch sliding characters. If she can see the wave coming (wizard eyes), she gets an extra second to prepare.
Anyone with a rope can anchor to something. But there's nothing to anchor TO on frictionless ice unless Davinia freezes an anchor point into the surface.
Kyboh ΓÇö heavy, strong ΓÇö can plant himself as a human wall for someone to crash into instead of sliding off the edge.
If they fail: Someone goes off the edge. Into the water. 6 irreducible cold damage, Might TN 14 (-2) to stay afloat. The floe tilts back but the edge where they fell off cracks away. -1 segment. Now they have a person in the water and a floe that's drifting away from them.
Rescuing someone from the water on frictionless ice: This is almost impossible alone. Reaching down to grab someone means you slide in after them. Solutions: Saijah air-dashes to the edge and grabs them (she can hold position). Davinia builds an ice ramp from the water to the deck. Two people form a chain ΓÇö one holds the other's legs while they reach down. Alfonso uses telekinetic magic to lift them out.

OBSTACLE 4: THE DRIFT
Warning: "The current is pulling you sideways. Not toward the glacier ΓÇö toward the open ocean. Davinia, you can feel it through the floe. The tonal field is weaker here. The ice under you is starting to grip ΓÇö which means your floe is slowing AND drifting west. You're going to miss the glacier entirely."
The problem: They're losing momentum and going off course. They need to generate thrust in a specific direction. This is a callback to Phase 1 ΓÇö but now they're mid-sea with no shore to push off of.
This obstacle rewards Alfonso. Raw magical force aimed in the right direction. Magic 19 means he can generate significant thrust. But he needs to aim precisely or he makes it worse.
Three-action solutions might include:
Alfonso fires a sustained force spell off the east side of the floe to push them west-to-north. Magic roll for precision.
Kyboh runs to the east edge and jumps off. His body mass at 30mph pushes the floe west. But now Kyboh is in the water or on another floe and has to get back. Heroic and stupid ΓÇö exactly what his player would do.
Orion uses the horn to vibrate the ice beneath them back to frictionless, restoring their speed. Tonal engineering roll ΓÇö he's fighting against the weakening resonance field.
Davinia reads the tonal field with her eyes and finds the "current" ΓÇö the direction the resonance is strongest. She can tell them which way to aim.
If they fail: The floe drifts off course. They pass the glacier. Now they have to figure out how to get BACK, which means generating force in a new direction with a smaller, damaged floe. No segment loss, but they add 2 more obstacles to their crossing as they correct course.

OBSTACLE 5: THE COLLISION
Warning: "Another floe. Bigger than yours. Moving perpendicular to your path. It's going to hit your port side in about ten seconds. There's no room to dodge. It's massive."
The problem: Physics problem. A larger mass hits a smaller mass. They need to either destroy the incoming floe, reinforce their floe, redirect the incoming floe's path, or ride the collision.
This obstacle is the hardest. It may require all five acting.
Three-action solutions might include:
Orion aims the horn at the incoming floe and tries to crack it into smaller pieces before impact. If he succeeds, they take scattered fragment hits instead of one massive collision.
Davinia builds a reinforced ice wall on the contact side to absorb impact. She can see exactly where the collision will happen.
Alfonso generates a force barrier or redirects the incoming floe with a massive push spell. Magic 19 means he CAN do this but the FP cost is brutal.
Kyboh braces on the impact side as a human shock absorber. He takes damage but reduces the collision force on the floe.
Saijah positions herself to grab whoever gets knocked loose.
If they partially succeed (2-3 good actions): Glancing blow. The incoming floe scrapes along their side, shearing off a strip. Everyone on that side makes Agility TN 12. -1 segment. The grinding sound is horrible. Ice dust fills the air.
If they fail: Direct broadside. The floe cracks down the middle. -3 segments. If the floe was already at 5 or below, it SPLITS. Half the party on each piece. The two halves drift apart. They must reconnect or one group reaches the glacier while the other doesn't.
The split scenario: This is the most dramatic thing that can happen. Two groups, two pieces of ice, drifting apart. Saijah can air-dash between them. Ropes can connect them. Alfonso can pull them together magically. But for a few terrible seconds, the party is divided on open water.

OBSTACLE 6: THE FOG
Warning: None for most of the party. The blizzard thickens into whiteout fog. Visibility drops to five feet. They can't see what's ahead.
The problem: They can't steer if they can't see. But Davinia CAN see. Her wizard eyes don't rely on visible light ΓÇö she sees magical architecture, tonal fields, aura. The ice, the obstacles, the glacier ΓÇö all visible to her through the fog as patterns of energy.
This is entirely Davinia's obstacle. She has to call directions while blind teammates execute. She is the eyes. They are the hands.
Three-action solutions might include:
Davinia stands at the front and calls out obstacles as she sees them through the tonal field. She becomes the navigator.
The other two actions are whatever she calls for ΓÇö "WALL LEFT, ALFONSO NOW" or "KYBOH BRACE FRONT, SOMETHING BIG"
Orion can use the horn as sonar ΓÇö sustained tones that bounce off obstacles and return. He can hear what's ahead even if he can't see it. If Davinia directs and Orion confirms, the party navigates blind.
If they fail (Davinia doesn't step up or calls wrong): They hit something unseen. Whatever it was, it wasn't huge ΓÇö but hitting something you never saw is terrifying. -1 segment. The fog clears in a few minutes either way. But the psychological damage is done. The table knows they need Davinia's eyes.
If Davinia navigates perfectly: She sees the path through the fog as a clear channel of tonal resonance threading between obstacles. She walks them through it with precise, calm instructions. The Crown approves. The whisper is warm: "You see the way. You always did." That's the trap ΓÇö the Crown making her feel powerful, needed, irreplaceable. Making the new eyes feel like a gift instead of a leash.
≡ƒæü∩╕Å DAVINIA SEES (Obstacle 6 ΓÇö the fog): While everyone else is blind, she sees everything. Not in color or light ΓÇö in structure. The ice is a lattice of glowing tonal lines. The obstacles are dark masses. The glacier ahead is a blazing beacon. The water is a void. Her friends are fragile halos of warmth on a field of cold geometry.
This is the most Ismara she has ever felt. This is how Ismara saw the world. Architecture. Systems. Not people ΓÇö structures to protect or discard.
If she says something kind to a teammate while navigating ΓÇö "You're doing great, stay left" ΓÇö the Crown goes quiet. If she says something cold and efficient ΓÇö "Move. Now. Left." ΓÇö the Crown hums with approval.

OBSTACLE 7: THE SHALLOWS
Warning: "The water is getting lighter. Not clearer ΓÇö shallower. Davinia, you can see the seafloor through the ice. There are rocks down there. Lots of them. Just barely submerged. You're going to run aground."
The problem: The floe is about to beach itself on submerged rocks. If it hits at speed, it shatters on the rocks. They need to slow down or lift the floe over the shallows.
This obstacle forces resource management. By now, Davinia's FP should be running low from building ice structures. Alfonso has been casting. Kyboh has been brute-forcing. The table has to decide who has enough left to act.
Three-action solutions might include:
Alfonso melts the ice on the underside of the floe at the front, creating a sloped hull that rides up over the rocks instead of hitting them flat.
Davinia freezes the shallow water solid ahead of them, creating an ice ramp over the rocks. This costs a LOT of FP.
Kyboh runs to the back and drags his feet (or his hands) off the trailing edge into the water to create drag. Painful ΓÇö the water is lethal cold. He takes damage voluntarily.
Orion uses the horn at low frequency aimed downward to vibrate the rocks into sand. Ambitious, but tonal engineering could do it.
If they fail: The floe grinds onto rocks. Horrible scraping sound. Everyone slides forward as the floe decelerates violently. Might TN 14 to stay standing. -2 segments from the bottom being torn up. The floe is now stuck. They have to push off the rocks to get moving again, which is a mini Phase-1 repeat with a smaller, damaged raft.

PHASE 3: THE WALL
This triggers when the glacier fills their entire field of vision.
Read aloud:
"The Singing Glacier is close. Close enough that you can see individual textures in the ice ΓÇö ancient, compressed, blue as sapphire. Close enough that the humming vibration is making your vision blur. Close enough that you realize you are moving very, very fast toward a wall of solid ice that has been here since before humans walked Tamriel.
You are going to hit it. You are going to hit it HARD. And the floe you're standing on has been cracking and shrinking for the last ten minutes.
You can see, set into the glacier face about thirty feet up, a dark opening. A cave. That's where you need to be. But right now you need to NOT BE DEAD."
The problem: Stop the floe. Everyone acts. This is not a three-action limit ΓÇö this is all hands on deck.
The math: Privately, assess how much speed they have. If they handled the gauntlet well (avoided most obstacles, still have momentum), they need MORE braking force. If they scraped through (hit everything, low speed), they need less. Scale the difficulty to make it tight but survivable.
What each character can contribute:
Davinia: Freeze the water ahead of the floe into a crumple zone. Thick ice that their floe crashes into and compresses rather than hitting the glacier directly. Alternatively, build an ice ramp that redirects their momentum upward toward the cave mouth. The ramp is harder but gets them where they need to go.


Kyboh: Run to the front of the floe and push against the glacier wall as they approach. He's the human brake pad. This will hurt him. He takes damage. But his Might can absorb some of the impact.


Alfonso: Reverse thrust. Everything he's got, aimed forward, pushing them back. This is the biggest spell he's cast all crossing.


Orion: Resonance brake. If the glacier is singing, it has a frequency. The horn can match it, creating constructive interference that pushes back against their momentum. Or destructive interference that cancels the vibration in the ice ahead, making it grippy ΓÇö restoring friction right before impact.


Saijah: She can't brake the floe. But she can save people. When the impact happens ΓÇö and it WILL happen, even if they brake ΓÇö people will fly forward off the floe. She air-dashes and catches them. Or she air-dashes to the cave mouth BEFORE impact and drops a rope.


Resolution:
If they brake successfully (4-5 contributions): The floe grinds to a halt against the glacier base. The impact is rough but survivable. No one goes into the water. The floe is done ΓÇö cracked, fractured, barely holding together. They step off onto the glacier's ice shelf. They made it.
If they partially brake (2-3 contributions): The floe hits the glacier at reduced speed. It cracks in half. Everyone takes 4 bludgeoning damage from impact. Characters on the front half are dumped onto the glacier shelf. Characters on the back half are on a sinking chunk of ice that's pulling away from the wall. They have one round to get off it ΓÇö jump, rope, Saijah's air dash, climb.
If they fail to brake (0-1 contributions): The floe detonates against the glacier. 8 bludgeoning damage to everyone. Everyone is in the water, in the rubble, against the glacier wall. They need to climb out of lethal water onto the ice shelf. Everyone makes Might TN 14 (-2) or Agility TN 14 to find a handhold. Saijah can air-dash out freely. This is survivable but EXPENSIVE ΓÇö they arrive at Hjolmar's door bruised, freezing, and humbled.
No matter what: They make it to the glacier. The question is what condition they're in when they arrive. The crossing should cost them something ΓÇö FP, HP, dignity ΓÇö but not their lives. Hjolmar's forge is inside. They didn't come this far to drown.
≡ƒæü∩╕Å DAVINIA SEES (Phase 3 ΓÇö the glacier wall): The glacier is the brightest thing she has ever seen with her new eyes. The entire structure is saturated with ancient tonal energy ΓÇö millennia of compressed sound and cold and time, layered into the ice like rings in a tree. The humming isn't random. It's language. Ice atronach language, the same script she saw on the Midden walls, but older. Much older. This glacier has been singing the same sentence since before the Dragon War.
She can't read it yet. Not the whole thing. But she catches one word, repeated, embedded in every layer of ancient ice:
PRESERVE.
CROWN REACTION: The Crown doesn't whisper. It SINGS. A single, clear note that harmonizes with the glacier's hum. Ismara is home. This is her architecture. Her ice. Her language. For one terrible, beautiful moment, Davinia doesn't know where she ends and Ismara begins.

