GM NOTES
Pacing: The whole crossing should take 30-45 minutes. Phase 1 is the longest (5-10 min of experimentation). Each obstacle in Phase 2 is 3-5 minutes. Phase 3 is 5-8 minutes.
Don't roll for everything. If their solution is clever and makes physical sense, it works. Roll only when the outcome is genuinely uncertain or when failure is interesting.
The floe tracker is your throttle. If they're handling it too easily, make the next collision cost more segments. If they're struggling, let a clever solution restore a segment ΓÇö Davinia freezes new ice onto the edges, Alfonso fuses a smaller floe to theirs.
Let them fail forward. Every failure makes the crossing harder but doesn't end it. The floe gets smaller. People are hurt. Resources are drained. But they keep moving toward the glacier. The only way to actually die is to stop trying.
Kyboh's gloves: His ceramic fused gloves are a liability AND an asset here. The psychic static is agonizing near the glacier. But the gloves respond to tonal frequencies ΓÇö on frictionless tonal ice, his punches have MORE force than normal, not less. He's dangerous to himself and to the floe. Let his player feel that.
This scene has no enemies. The ice is the enemy. The physics is the enemy. The clock is the enemy. If you add combat (wraiths, sea creatures), it dilutes the purity of the challenge. The whole point is that they're fighting Newton, not monsters.

